import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# ML models
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Evaluation metrics
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv("your_dataset.csv")  # Replace with actual filename

# Check for nulls
print(df.isnull().sum())

# Optional: Visualize target distribution
sns.countplot(x='Purchased', data=df)
plt.title("Target Class Distribution")
plt.show()

# Split features and target
X = df[['Age', 'EstimatedSalary']]
y = df['Purchased']

# Feature Scaling
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Train-test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

In[8]:
models = {
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(),
    "K-Nearest Neighbors": KNeighborsClassifier(),
    "SVM": SVC(probability=True),
    "Decision Tree": DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier()
}

results = []

for name, model in models.items():
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    results.append({
        "Model": name,
        "Accuracy": accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred),
        "Precision": precision_score(y_test, y_pred),
        "Recall": recall_score(y_test, y_pred),
        "F1 Score": f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    })

results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
print(results_df.sort_values(by="Accuracy", ascending=False))

In[12]:
# Use best model (e.g., Random Forest) - update based on results
best_model = RandomForestClassifier()
best_model.fit(X_scaled, y)

def predict_custom(age, salary):
    if salary is None:
        salary = df['EstimatedSalary'].mean()  # Fill missing salary with mean or median
    input_scaled = scaler.transform([[age, salary]])
    prediction = best_model.predict(input_scaled)
    return "Will Purchase" if prediction[0] == 1 else "Will Not Purchase"

# First group
scenarios_1 = [(30, 87000), (40, None), (40, 100000), (50, None)]
for age, salary in scenarios_1:
    print(f"Age: {age}, Salary: {salary} -> {predict_custom(age, salary)}")

# Second group
scenarios_2 = [(18, None), (22, 600000), (35, 2500000), (60, 100000000)]
for age, salary in scenarios_2:
    print(f"Age: {age}, Salary: {salary} -> {predict_custom(age, salary)}")

X = df[['Age', 'EstimatedSalary']]
y = df['Purchased']

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Split the data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Train KNN model
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)
knn.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Function to plot decision boundaries
def plot_decision_boundary(X, y, model, title):
    h = 0.01
    x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
    y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min, x_max, h),
                         np.arange(y_min, y_max, h))
    Z = model.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, alpha=0.3, cmap=plt.cm.RdYlBu)
    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, s=40, edgecolor='k', cmap=plt.cm.RdYlBu)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Age (scaled)')
    plt.ylabel('EstimatedSalary (scaled)')
    plt.show()

# Plot decision boundary
plot_decision_boundary(X_scaled, y, knn, "KNN Decision Boundary - Insurance Purchase Prediction")

# Scenarios for prediction
scenarios = pd.DataFrame([
    [30, 87000],
    [40, 0],
    [40, 100000],
    [50, 0],
    [18, 0],
    [22, 600000],
    [35, 2500000],
    [60, 100000000]
], columns=['Age', 'EstimatedSalary'])

# Scale scenarios using the same scaler
scenarios_scaled = scaler.transform(scenarios)

# Predict outcomes
predictions = knn.predict(scenarios_scaled)

# Combine predictions with input
scenarios['Predicted Purchase'] = predictions
print(scenarios)

    "To develop an AI-based model that predicts whether a customer will purchase insurance based on their "

)

    "- Features: Age, EstimatedSalary\n"
    "- Target: Purchased (1 = Yes, 0 = No)\n"
    "- Dataset Size: 400 rows\n"
    "- Preprocessing:\n"
    "  - Missing values handled (if any)\n"
    "  - Feature scaling (StandardScaler)\n"
    "  - Train-Test Split: 80%-20%"
)

hdr_cells[0].text = 'Model'
hdr_cells[1].text = 'Accuracy'
hdr_cells[2].text = 'Precision'

    ("K-Nearest Neighbors", "92.5%", "86.7%", "92.9%", "89.7%"),
    ("Support Vector Machine", "92.5%", "84.4%", "96.4%", "90.0%"),
    ("Random Forest", "90.0%", "81.3%", "92.9%", "86.7%"),
    ("Logistic Regression", "86.3%", "90.5%", "67.9%", "77.6%"),
    ("Decision Tree", "83.8%", "77.8%", "75.0%", "76.4%")
]
for model in model_data:
    row_cells = table.add_row().cells

# Save the document

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from docx import Document
from docx.shared import Inches
import os

# Assuming model is your best trained model (e.g., knn or svm)
# and scaler was used to standardize features
# and df is your original DataFrame

# Use SVM as best model (replace with KNN if desired)
best_model = svm  # Or use knn
scaler = StandardScaler()
X = df[['Age', 'EstimatedSalary']]
y = df['Purchased']
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Refit the model on full data
best_model.fit(X_scaled, y)

# --- Graphical Analysis ---
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='Age', y='EstimatedSalary', hue='Purchased', palette='Set1')
plt.title("Customer Insurance Purchase Distribution")
plt.tight_layout()
plot_path = "purchase_plot.png"
plt.savefig(plot_path)
plt.close()

# --- Predictions for scenarios ---
scenarios = [
    (30, 87000),
    (40, 0),
    (40, 100000),
    (50, 0),
    (18, 0),
    (22, 600000),
    (35, 2500000),
    (60, 100000000)
]

scenario_preds = []
for age, salary in scenarios:
    scaled_input = scaler.transform([[age, salary]])
    prediction = best_model.predict(scaled_input)[0]
    scenario_preds.append((age, salary, prediction))

# --- Generate Word Report ---
doc = Document()
doc.add_heading('Customer Insurance Purchase Prediction - Detailed Report', 0)

# Add plot
doc.add_heading(' Data Distribution Plot', level=1)
doc.add_paragraph("This scatter plot shows the distribution of customers based on age and estimated salary.")
doc.add_picture(plot_path, width=Inches(5.5))

# Prediction results
doc.add_heading(' Predictions on Given Scenarios', level=1)
table = doc.add_table(rows=1, cols=3)
hdr_cells = table.rows[0].cells
hdr_cells[0].text = 'Age'
hdr_cells[1].text = 'Estimated Salary'
hdr_cells[2].text = 'Purchased (1=Yes, 0=No)'

for age, salary, pred in scenario_preds:
    row_cells = table.add_row().cells
    row_cells[0].text = str(age)
    row_cells[1].text = str(salary)
    row_cells[2].text = str(pred)

# Save final report
doc.save("Final_Insurance_Model_Report.docx")

# Clean up image file if needed
if os.path.exists(plot_path):
    os.remove(plot_path)
